          "body": "Verses 6-9 narrate the precise moment Saul's relationship with David becomes irreparable. The women of Israel sing a comparative song — Saul his thousands, David his ten thousands — and Saul hears it not as celebration but as arithmetic. He performs the calculation with lethal precision: ten thousands minus thousands equals the kingdom (18:8). The narrator is showing us what envy does to perception: a song of national celebration becomes, in Saul's ears, a coronation anthem for his rival. Saul's anger (*charah*, literally 'to burn') is the same root used of God's burning anger against Israel's idolatry. The language is not accidental. Saul's jealousy has a quasi-religious intensity — it is the burning of a man who has made his throne his god and now perceives that god to be threatened. From this moment, the narrator tells us, Saul 'looked at David with suspicion from that day on' (18:9). The Hebrew (*avan*) conveys a calculating, watchful eye — not a glance but a sustained surveillance. Jealousy, once born from a single lyric, never sleeps again."
