          "body": "Verses 17-27 constitute one of Scripture's most calculated portraits of hypocrisy in power. Saul offers David his older daughter Merab with a military condition attached — 'fight the LORD's battles' — while privately intending that the Philistines will do what Saul's own hand cannot (18:17). When Merab is given to another (18:19), Saul learns that his younger daughter Michal loves David (18:20) and recognizes a second opportunity: the love can become a 'snare' (*moqesh*, a trap, the word used for the traps of idolatry in Deuteronomy 7:16). He then deploys his servants as disinformation agents, instructing them to speak secretly to David about the king's delight in him (18:22) — the opposite of the truth. The dowry he names (100 Philistine foreskins) is a suicide mission in disguise. David's response is to bring 200 (18:27). The irony accumulates at every layer: the marriage designed as a death trap becomes a royal alliance; the dowry designed as a death sentence becomes a double military triumph; the woman Saul hoped would be a snare to David will in fact save David's life (19:11-17). The chapter is not simply demonstrating Saul's evil; it is demonstrating that schemes against God's anointed fold back on themselves. Spurgeon noted on Psalm 33 that God makes the counsel of nations fail — He bends their purposes to serve His own."
