        "body": "The second half of chapter 18 (18:17-27) is a masterclass in the narrator's use of irony as a theological instrument. Saul conceives two marriage schemes — Merab (18:17-19) and Michal (18:20-27) — and both are designed as death traps. Both are announced in the narrator's terms as schemes (*Saul thought*, 18:17, 21; *Saul planned*, 18:25) rather than legitimate offers. The reader is given access to Saul's internal reasoning precisely so that the ironic reversal can be felt at full force when each scheme produces the opposite of its intended outcome.\n\nThe Merab gambit (18:17-19) collapses when Merab is given to someone else — the text does not explain why (2 Sam 21:8 provides Adriel's name with no explanation). The brevity is pointed: Saul's first murder-by-marriage scheme simply evaporates, without David being harmed and without Saul having an excuse to refuse. The Michal scheme (18:20-27) is more elaborate and its irony more devastating. Saul uses his servants as disinformation agents (18:22) — instructing them to tell David that the king delights in him while intending to use the marriage as a trap. The 100-foreskin dowry (18:25) is almost certainly a death sentence: fighting into Philistine territory to kill and mutilate 100 enemy combatants without dying in the attempt was designed to be impossible.\n\nDavid brings 200 (18:27). The doubling is not incidental; it is the narrator's way of showing that the impossible becomes the occasion for supernatural triumph when the LORD is with the combatant. Every Philistine foreskin is a refutation of Saul's plan. The dowry that was meant to end in David's death ends in David's royal marriage, his public military honor, and his permanent installation in the king's family. Saul has used his daughter's love as a weapon and managed only to give his enemy a queen.\n\nThe theological pattern here is what the wisdom literature calls the reversal of the wicked man's schemes against the righteous — Psalm 7:15-16 is the canonical formula: 'He has dug a pit and hollowed it out, and has fallen into the hole which he made. His mischief will return upon his own head, and his violence will descend upon his own pate.' Saul is not an exception to this pattern; he is its definitive narrative illustration in Samuel.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Moqesh* (snare, 18:21) — the same word used for the snare of foreign gods in Exodus 23:33, Deuteronomy 7:16, and Psalm 106:36. By using this word, the narrator signals that Saul is treating his own daughter the way idolatry treats worshipers — as a trap. *Mohar* (dowry, 18:25) — the bride-price paid by the groom to the bride's family, normally in silver or goods. Saul's demand for 100 Philistine foreskins as mohar is a grotesque inversion of the institution: marriage-price as death-assignment."
